#PerfectPlanet takeover by @dolphindronedom

“The first clip features a humpback whale rising from the middle of a baitball in absolutely perfect conditions! This whale's name is Snowflake. Snowflake is a very special whale to me as it is the first humpback whale I ever saw breach, and the first whale that ever ‘mugged’ me…

“In the whale watching world, ‘mugging’ refers to the moment a whale sticks its head out of the water, making eye contact. Snowflake seemed to recognise our voices. It was a beautiful and life changing moment.”

A Perfect Planet tells the story of Earth's power and fragility. Oceans are the largest ecosystem on Earth, covering two thirds of our world’s surface and providing half the oxygen in our atmosphere. They’re home to as much as 80% of all life on earth, and nearly three billion people rely on them for their primary source of food.⁣⁣

For more about A Perfect Planet and where to watch, click the link in our bio.⁣⁣

Looking in the mirror first thing like 🙃⁣

Indigenous to Unguja, the Zanzibar red colobus monkey (Piliocolobus kirkii) is born with a black and white coat but matures to develop hair ranging from dark red to black. Part of their diet involves eating the leaves of non-native tree species such the Indian almond and mango trees. They also eat charcoal to counteract the effects of the toxins inside the leaves, which helps them with digestion. ⁣

Dolphin drifting 🐬⁣
⁣
These dolphins are hunting in waters only a few centimetres deep, using a technique called hydroplaning. As fish move into shallower water, the dolphins usual hunting techniques no longer work. Instead they pump their tails to gain speed and hydroplane, allowing them to catch fish even in the shallowest waters. ⁣
⁣

If it first you don't succeed…🐻🐟⁣
⁣
Grizzly bears (Ursus arctos horribilis) will battle for best fishing spots to catch salmon swimming upstream. ⁣The fish will make small leaps to gauge where the bears are, but this can often lead straight to getting caught! It's not a completely impossible journey however, as for every salmon caught, hundreds make it past the bears.⁣
⁣

Sharing is caring 😍⁣
⁣
The great hornbill, or great Indian hornbill (Buceros bicornis) is recognisable by its vibrant casque atop its colourful bill. The casque serves no obvious purpose, however it can be used during mating rituals in 'casque butting' exercises. They help to disperse fruit seeds in the forests they reside in via their droppings, which has given them the nickname 'farmers of the forest'. ⁣

When the sun does wonders for your hair 💇⁣
 ⁣
The adaptable red fox (Vulpes vulpes) is found in various terrains, inhabiting Europe, temperate Asia, North America and Northern Africa. Like a cat’s tail, the red fox’s ‘brush’ aids balance, but may also be used as cover in cold weather, as well as a means of communication with other foxes. Red foxes continue to adjust to human-dominated environments by becoming increasingly nocturnal and bold in their behaviour.⁣
 ⁣

Peekaboo 🙈⁣
⁣
The gray langur (Semnopithecus entellus) can be found across a plethora of habitats, from arid deserts to tropical evergreen rainforests. It is also not uncommon to spot them roaming the temples and villages of India and Nepal. They are vocal creatures and use a variety of sounds to communicate different needs, from alerting other troop members to danger to attracting a mate. ⁣

POV: the patronising 'head tilt' 🙄⁣
⁣
Endemic to the Indian subcontinent, the yellow-wattled lapwing (Vanellus malabaricus) can be found in scrub habitats, open or dry stony grasslands. Distinguishable characteristics in breeding adults include its vibrant yellow facial wattles, solid black cap, white belly and long yellow legs. Other notable features include its rapid flight and sharp call. ⁣

Also known as the 'rock eagle-owl' or 'bengal eagle owl', the Indian eagle owl (Bubo bengalensis) can be found on the Indian subcontinent. Example prey may include rats, mice or even birds equivalent in size to a peafowl. One tactic they use to confuse predators when fending for their young, is to feign a wing injury, or fly in a zigzag direction. ⁣
